metadata.name: Ari's Thread #123
metadata.description:
I side with the idea that we made this reality so weird merely to satisfy our -psychotic- need to overcomplicate things. Not you, of course.

That's why I believe that our choices don't "create our own path" but a maze for others to (try to) solve.
This God or that One or none, the old songs or the new ones, rooting for or against…
The deepest we meet into each other's maze, the more choices we share. Reciprocally, when we lack the interest to explore even a couple of turns, we're but a first impression to each other.

This work examines those ideas by continually presenting options to N individuals and then tracking their choices, which in turn generates different outputs at different depths.

To access them:
- press "S" for story mode, the sequence of choices
  - then, press "1" through "5" to change the speed
- press "L" for landscape, the first impression
- press "D" to see the details and view the mazes (may take a while)

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #96
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.name: COMPUTERS #28
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and classic noise algorithms.

COMPUTERS is a meditation on the aesthetics of computing in all of its forms. It recalls the types of computation required to build temples, write complex texts, weave detailed textiles, and program computer games. Pixels have always existed in some form or another, before and after the screen. Every iteration of COMPUTERS suggests that computation is both contemporary and ancient.

Press 'p' or click to pause the animation.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #111
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pewén, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the Wünelfe star, and the staggered cross Ngümin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

–

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

Patricio Isaías, September 2022

metadata.name: TI·ME 0 #23
metadata.description:
How and when Time started has always been one of the biggest questions of the humankind, that is yet to be answered.

There are things we may know, and there are things we may never know. Though, one thing that may be considered as certain is that, it did not start before it was started to be measured.

* * *

This generative artwork is a gift to my dear collectors of TI·ME series (TI·ME I, TI·ME II & TI·ME III).

Any collector who is holding 3 or more pieces of any of the three TI·ME collections mentioned above at the snapshot time of Aug 22, 18:00 UTC, will receive a piece from TI·ME 0 sent to their wallet. One piece per each 3 pieces held, i.e., if you have 9 pieces in total from any TI·ME collections combined, you will receive 3 pieces. Remaining pieces (if any), will be sent to randomly selected collectors who have less than 3 pieces.

Thank you very much for collecting and for your continuous support. Only with that, I can continue to do what I love.

metadata.name: Forgotten Memories #188
metadata.description:
Memories can be dark or they can be bright. Sometimes they are faint and pale, sometimes they are vivid and colorful. Sometimes they are hard to forget, sometimes they are easy to remember.

Memories are easily interrupted or even fractured, but they are also mostly always connected with other memories, whether they are related or not.

Forgotten Memories is what I consider to be my most ambitious study of color harmony yet. Each color represents a different category of memory, which are stored in our mind in layers of time. Their shapes differ in width and length depending on how weak/strong the memory was and how long it lasted.

Once a memory is forgotten, it may or may never be remembered again. But one thing that is not to be forgotten is that whether we choose to forget or remember, we are made of our memories.

* * *

Press S to save as PNG.
Press 1 to save with 1000px height.
Press 2 to save with 2000px height.

The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

metadata.name: Zena #139
metadata.description:
Zena is a study of creating complex patterns via manipulating particle angles using math, bitwise operators and noise.

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

----Best experienced in full screen----

Probabilities;

- 7 different patterns

- 4 frame types

- 2 frame colors

- 4 different particle hues (Rare; full spectrum) 

- Rare; circular placement

- Rare; dark background

You can right click and save as .png (or press 's' in liveMode) once the rendering is done.



Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, September 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Up Above #256
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the feeling of insignificance. This feeling, which we all share and feel at some points in our lives is often referred to as negative. But I feel quite the contrary, this feeling is quite beautiful, as it shows small parts together can form something big.

We are but a speck in the universe, like a grain of sand on a beach, like a single drop of water in an ocean, like a single leaf on a tree. But together we are a forest, a river, a sea. Together we are the universe.

Feel free to explore this piece for as long as you want, and feel free to export it in any way you like, and use it for thing like prints, and, of course, I'd love to know about them :)

---

To export your iteration, click the menu bar at the bottom of the screen and press either the "Export current" or "Export custom" button.

We meander through the flows of life, alone but together. This experience — an ultimately solitary one — is communicated but never truly shared. Our consciousnesses live in a perpetual separated state, alone but together.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #35
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.
